te book |last1=Schreiber |first1=Gerhard |title=Die Italienischen Milit\u00e4rinternierten Im Deutschen Machtbereich 1943-1945: Verachtet - Verraten - Vergessen (Beitr\u00e4ge Zur Milit\u00e4rgeschichte) |date=1990 |publisher=De Gruyter Oldenbourg |isbn=978-3486553918 |language=German |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Thomsen |first1=Birgit N\u00fcchel |title=Kollaboration eller tilpasning? |date=2009 |url=http://xn--vrnemagerne-98a.dk/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Kollaboration.pdf |accessdate=18 December 2019 |language=Danish |isbn=9788793068452 |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n;Online\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite web |last1=Altenburger |first1=Andreas |title=Befehlshaber |url=http://www.lexikon-der-wehrmacht.de/Gliederungen/BefehlshaberHeer/GliederungBefehlshaber-R.htm |website=Lexikon der Wehrmacht |date=n.d. |accessdate=8 February 2018 |language=German |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web |author1=Bundesarchiv |title=BArch Bild 146-1969-041-30 |url=https://www.bundesarchiv.de/DE/Content/Virtuelle-Ausstellungen/Die-Deutschen-Heeresgruppen-Teil-2-Zweiter-Weltkrieg/032__alexander-l-hr_PDF.pdf?__blob=publicationFile |accessdate=4 September 2019 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web |author1=Bundesarchiv1 |title=BArch RW 36 Milit\u00e4rbefehlshaber Belgien-Nordfrankreich |url=https://invenio.bundesarchiv.de/basys2-invenio/main.xhtml;jsessionid=GJx6sHx3IqAyyAQFDwyN42Xd |website=invenio.bundesarchiv.de |publisher=Bundesarchiv |accessdate=18 December 2019 |location=Freiburg |language=German |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web |author1=Bundesarchiv2 |title=BArch RW 38 Wehrmachtbefehlshaber in D\u00e4nemark |url=https://invenio.bundesarchiv.de/invenio/direktlink/4bd804ef-8fb6-4575-91e8-b85bcc4182bd/ |website=invenio.bundesarchiv.de |publisher=Bundesarchiv |accessdate=18 December 2019 |location=Freiburg |language=German |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web |author1=Bundesarchiv3 |title=BArch RW 37 Wehrmachtbefehlshaber in den Niederlanden |url=https://invenio.bundesarchiv.de/invenio/direktlink/7b312493-077b-4777-86ca-0389f973cdff/ |website=invenio.bundesarchiv.de |publisher=Bundesarchiv |accessdate=18 December 2019 |location=Freiburg |language=German |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web |author1=Bundesarchiv4 |title=BArch RW 39/Wehrmachtbefehlshaber in Norwegen |url=https://invenio.bundesarchiv.de/invenio/direktlink/83d27528-5974-4f61-8f43-d3a44acd77a7/ |website=invenio.bundesarchiv.de |publisher=Bundesarchiv |accessdate=18 December 2019 |location=Freiburg |language=German |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web |author1=Bundesarchiv5 |title=BArch RW 41/74: Territoriale Befehlshaber in der Sowjetunion |url=https://invenio.bundesarchiv.de/invenio/direktlink/b11b1027-7d93-4ac2-9f0a-a5eae058b782/ |website=invenio.bundesarchiv.de |publisher=Bundesarchiv |accessdate=18 December 2019 |language=German |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web |author=Court of Hanover |title=Justiz und NS-Verbrechen: Lfd.Nr.683 |url=http://www1.jur.uva.nl/junsv/Excerpts/683003.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060831204730/http://www1.jur.uva.nl/junsv/Excerpts/683003.htm |archivedate=31 August 2006 |language=German |date=27 June 1968 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web |last1=Dimitri |first1=Roden |title=Duits burgerlijk bestuur (Zivilverwaltung) |url=https://www.belgiumwwii.be/nl/belgie-in-oorlog/artikels/duits-burgerlijk-bestuur-zivilverwaltung.html |website=belgiumwwii.be |accessdate=31 March 2020 |date=n.d. |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web |last1=Hitler |first1=Adolf |title=F\u00fchrerweisung Nr. 40, 23.3.1942 |url=https://bunkermuseumhanstholm.dk/viden-om/dokumenter-1940-45/vaernemagtens-overkommando-okw-vedr-danmark/fuehrerweisung-nr-40-2331942/ |website=Bunker Museum Hanstholm |accessdate=28 August 2019 |language=German |date=23 March 1942 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web |author1=Jersey War Tours |title=Graf Von Schmettow Interview |url=https://www.jerseybunkertours.com/graf-von-schmettow-interview |website=Jersey War Tours |accessdate=18 December 2019 |date=n.d. |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web |author1=MMG |title=Werner Kempf |url=http://www.ritterkreuztraeger.info/rkel/k/EL111Kempf.pdf |website=ritterkreuztraeger.info |accessdate=18 December 2019 |language=German |date=5 January 2010 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web |author1=NIOD |title=Wehrmachtbefehlshaber in den Niederlanden |url=https://www.archieven.nl/nl/zoeken?miview=inv2&mivast=0&mizig=210&miadt=298&micode=001&milang=nl |website=archieven.nl |date=5 May 2017 |accessdate=8 May 2019 |language=Dutch |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://museumscenterhanstholm.dk/en/learn-more/documents-1940-1945/commander-in-chief-of-the-german-army-in-denmark/ War diary of the Commander-in-chief of the German Army in Denmark, 1943-1945] (''in German'')\n", "name_user": "Skjoldbro", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wehrmachtbefehlshaber"}
{"title_page": "Matte Kudasai", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2013}}\n{{ref improve|date=February 2016}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Matte Kudasai\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[King Crimson]]\n| album      = [[Discipline (King Crimson album)|Discipline]]\n| B-side     = Elephant Talk\n| released   = September 1981\n| format     =\n| recorded   = 1981\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Progressive rock]]\n| length     = 3:47\n| label      = [[Warner Bros.]]\n| writer     = [[Adrian Belew]], [[Bill Bruford]], [[Robert Fripp]], [[Tony Levin]]\n| producer   = King Crimson, [[Rhett Davies]]\n| prev_title = [[Epitaph (King Crimson song)|Epitaph]]/[[21st Century Schizoid Man]]\n| prev_year  = 1976\n| next_title = Elephant Talk\n| next_year  = 1981\n}}\n\"'''Matte Kudasai'''\" is a single by the [[progressive rock]] band [[King Crimson]], released in 1981. Both songs from the single appear on the album ''[[Discipline (King Crimson album)|Discipline]]'' (1981). \"Matte Kudasai\" evolved from another song recorded by [[The League of Gentlemen (band)|The League of Gentlemen]] called \"Northa Kudasai\", which in turn became \"North Star\" on [[Robert Fripp]]'s 1979 album ''[[Exposure (Robert Fripp album)|Exposure]]''.\n\nThe 30th and 35th anniversary editions of ''Discipline'' contain two versions of \"Matte Kudasai\". On the original LP, cassette and CD releases, just one version was included. That version featured a guitar overdub by [[Robert Fripp]]. \"Matte Kudasai (Alternative version)\" (as it appears as a bonus track on current{{when}} editions) is the original version included on the LP .\n\nAdrian Belew applies a slide and echo to his guitar to simulate the sound of seagulls twice in the song; once at the beginning, and again near the end. \"Matte Kudasai\" means \"wait, please\" in [[Japanese language|Japanese]].{{citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\n==Track listing==\n#\"Matte Kudasai\" (special mix) ([[Adrian Belew]], [[Bill Bruford]], [[Robert Fripp]], [[Tony Levin]])\n#\"[[Elephant Talk (song)|Elephant Talk]]\" (Belew, Bruford, Fripp, Levin)\n\n==Personnel==\n*[[Robert Fripp]] \u2013 [[Roland Corporation|Roland G-303 guitar synthesizer controller]], Roland GR-300 [[guitar synthesizer]]\n*[[Adrian Belew]] \u2013 [[electric guitar|guitar]], [[Singing|vocals]]\n*[[Tony Levin]] \u2013 [[Music Man StingRay|Music Man Stingray 4 bass]]\n*[[Bill Bruford]] \u2013 [[Drum kit|drums]]\n\n==Covers==\nOn 7 February 2011, [[Kurt Elling]] released the album [[The Gate (Kurt Elling album)|The Gate]], with a version of the song as the opening track.\n\nOn 20 April 2011, [[k.d. lang]] and her band the Siss Boom Bang covered the song as part of her concert at the BBC Radio Theater. The audio and video of that performance were [http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b010dkbz#segments broadcast on 21 April 2011 on BBC Radio 2]. Lang noted in her introduction to the song that it was influential on the sound of her fifth album, ''[[Ing\u00e9nue (album)|Ingenue]]''.{{Verify source|date=February 2020}}\n\nIn late 2005, Voiceprint released the first [[Crimson Jazz Trio]] album, ''The King Crimson Songbook, Volume One'' with an instrumental version of the song, featuring fretless bass work by [[Tim Landers]]. The [[Crimson Jazz Trio]] was a short-lived jazz trio conceived by former [[King Crimson]] drummer [[Ian Wallace (drummer)|Ian Wallace]] and pianist Jody Nardone. The trio folded after Wallace's death in February 2007.\n\nThe Levin Brothers (keyboardist/arranger [[Pete Levin]] and King Crimson bassist [[Tony Levin]]) included an instrumental version of \"Matte Kudasai\" on their 2014 album ''Levin Brothers''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thelevinbrothers.com/#THEALBUM|title=The Levin Brothers Homepage|website=Thelevinbrothers.com|accessdate=2016-10-19}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|king-crimson|matte-kudasai}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{King Crimson}}\n\n[[Category:King Crimson songs]]\n[[Category:1981 singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Adrian Belew]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Robert Fripp]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Bill Bruford]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Tony Levin]]\n[[Category:1981 songs]]\n[[Category:Warner Records singles]]\n\n\n{{1980s-rock-song-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2013}}\n{{ref improve|date=February 2016}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Matte Kudasai\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[King Crimson]]\n| album      = [[Discipline (King Crimson album)|Discipline]]\n| B-side     = Elephant Talk\n| released   = September 1981\n| format     =\n| recorded   = 1981\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Progressive rock]]\n| length     = 3:47\n| label      = [[Warner Bros.]]\n| writer     = [[Adrian Belew]], [[Bill Bruford]], [[Robert Fripp]], [[Tony Levin]]\n| producer   = King Crimson, [[Rhett Davies]]\n| prev_title = [[Epitaph (King Crimson song)|Epitaph]]/[[21st Century Schizoid Man]]\n| prev_year  = 1976\n| next_title = Elephant Talk\n| next_year  = 1981\n}}\n\"'''Matte Kudasai'''\" is a single by the [[progressive rock]] band [[King Crimson]], released in 1981. Both songs from the single appear on the album ''[[Discipline (King Crimson album)|Discipline]]'' (1981). \"Matte Kudasai\" evolved from another song recorded by [[The League of Gentlemen (band)|The League of Gentlemen]] called \"Northa Kudasai\", which in turn became \"North Star\" on [[Robert Fripp]]'s 1979 album ''[[Exposure (Robert Fripp album)|Exposure]]''.\n\nThe 30th and 35th anniversary editions of ''Discipline'' contain two versions of \"Matte Kudasai\". On the original LP, cassette and CD releases, just one version was included. That version featured a guitar overdub by [[Robert Fripp]]. \"Matte Kudasai (Alternative version)\" (as it appears as a bonus track on current editions) is the original version included on the LP .\n\nAdrian Belew applies a slide and echo to his guitar to simulate the sound of seagulls twice in the song; once at the beginning, and again near the end. \"Matte Kudasai\" means \"wait, please\" in [[Japanese language|Japanese]].{{citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\n==Track listing==\n#\"Matte Kudasai\" (special mix) ([[Adrian Belew]], [[Bill Bruford]], [[Robert Fripp]], [[Tony Levin]])\n#\"[[Elephant Talk (song)|Elephant Talk]]\" (Belew, Bruford, Fripp, Levin)\n\n==Personnel==\n*[[Robert Fripp]] \u2013 [[Roland Corporation|Roland G-303 guitar synthesizer controller]], Roland GR-300 [[guitar synthesizer]]\n*[[Adrian Belew]] \u2013 [[electric guitar|guitar]], [[Singing|vocals]]\n*[[Tony Levin]] \u2013 [[Music Man StingRay|Music Man Stingray 4 bass]]\n*[[Bill Bruford]] \u2013 [[Drum kit|drums]]\n\n==Covers==\nOn 7 February 2011, [[Kurt Elling]] released the album [[The Gate (Kurt Elling album)|The Gate]], with a version of the song as the opening track.\n\nOn 20 April 2011, [[k.d. lang]] and her band the Siss Boom Bang covered the song as part of her concert at the BBC Radio Theater. The audio and video of that performance were [http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b010dkbz#segments broadcast on 21 April 2011 on BBC Radio 2]. Lang noted in her introduction to the song that it was influential on the sound of her fifth album, ''[[Ing\u00e9nue (album)|Ingenue]]''.{{Verify source|date=February 2020}}\n\nIn late 2005, Voiceprint released the first [[Crimson Jazz Trio]] album, ''The King Crimson Songbook, Volume One'' with an instrumental version of the song, featuring fretless bass work by [[Tim Landers]]. The [[Crimson Jazz Trio]] was a short-lived jazz trio conceived by former [[King Crimson]] drummer [[Ian Wallace (drummer)|Ian Wallace]] and pianist Jody Nardone. The trio folded after Wallace's death in February 2007.\n\nThe Levin Brothers (keyboardist/arranger [[Pete Levin]] and King Crimson bassist [[Tony Levin]]) included an instrumental version of \"Matte Kudasai\" on their 2014 album ''Levin Brothers''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thelevinbrothers.com/#THEALBUM|title=The Levin Brothers Homepage|website=Thelevinbrothers.com|accessdate=2016-10-19}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|king-crimson|matte-kudasai}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{King Crimson}}\n\n[[Category:King Crimson songs]]\n[[Category:1981 singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Adrian Belew]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Robert Fripp]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Bill Bruford]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Tony Levin]]\n[[Category:1981 songs]]\n[[Category:Warner Records singles]]\n\n\n{{1980s-rock-song-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Cherkash", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matte_Kudasai"}
{"title_page": "Hyperinsulinemia", "text_new": "{{short description|Abnormal increase in insulin in the bloodstream relative to glucose}}\n{{Infobox medical condition (new) \n| name            =  \n| image           = InsulinMonomer.jpg \n| caption         = Insulin binding to its receptor \n| pronounce       =  \n| field           =  \n| synonyms        = '''Hyperinsulinaemia'''\n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n'''Hyperinsulinemia''',  is a condition in which there are excess levels of [[insulin]] circulating in the blood relative to the level of glucose. While it is often mistaken for [[diabetes]] or [[hyperglycaemia]], hyperinsulinemia can result from a variety of metabolic diseases and conditions. While hyperinsulinemia is often seen in people with early stage type 2 diabetes mellitus, it is not the cause of the condition and is only one symptom of the disease. Type 1 diabetes only occurs when pancreatic beta-cell function is impaired. Hyperinsulinemia can be seen in a variety of conditions including [[diabetes mellitus type 2]], in neonates and in drug induced hyperinsulinemia. It can also occur in congenital hyperinsulism, including [[nesidioblastosis]].\n\nHyperinsulinemia is associated with [[hypertension]], [[obesity]], [[dyslipidemia]], and [[glucose intolerance]].<ref name=\"pmid3884667\">{{cite journal|last=Modan|first=Michaela|author2=Halkin H |author3=Almog S |author4=Lusky A |author5=Eshkol A |author6=Shefi M |author7=Shitrit A |author8=Fuchs Z. |title=Hyperinsulinemia: A link between hypertension obesity and glucose intolerance|journal=J. Clin. Invest.|date=March 1985|volume=75|issue=3|pages=809\u201317|doi=10.1172/JCI111776|pmid=3884667|pmc=423608}}</ref> These conditions are collectively known as [[Metabolic syndrome]].<ref name=\"pmid19435961\">{{cite journal|last=Danker|first=Rache|author2=Chetrit A |author3=Shanik MH |author4=Raz I |author5=Roth J |title=Basal-stat hyperinsulinemia in healthy normoglycemic adults is predictive of type 2 diabetes over a 24-year follow-up|journal=Diabetes Care|date=August 2009|volume=32|issue=8|pages=1464\u201366|doi=10.2337/dc09-0153|pmid=19435961|pmc=2713622}}</ref> This close association between hyperinsulinemia and conditions of metabolic syndrome suggest related or common mechanisms of pathogenicity.<ref name=\"pmid3884667\" /> Hyperinsulinemia has been shown to \"play a role in obese [[hypertension]] by increasing renal sodium retention\".<ref name=\"pmid3884667\" />\n\nIn type 2 diabetes, the cells of the body become resistant to the effects of insulin as the receptors which bind to the hormone become less sensitive to insulin concentrations resulting in hyperinsulinemia and disturbances in insulin release.<ref name=\"name\">{{cite journal | last1 = Shanik | first1 = M.H. | last2 = Yuping | first2 = X. | last3 = Skrha | first3 = J. | last4 = Danker | first4 = R. | last5 = Zick | first5 = Y. | last6 = Roth | first6 = J. | year = 2008 | title = Insulin Resistance and Hyperinsulinemia | url = http://care.diabetesjournals.org/content/31/Supplement_2/S262.full | journal = Diabetes Care | volume = 31 | issue = 2| pages = S262\u201368 | doi =  10.2337/dc08-s264| pmid = 18227495 }}</ref> With a reduced response to insulin, the [[beta cells]] of the pancreas secrete increasing amounts of insulin in response to the continued high blood glucose levels resulting in hyperinsulinemia. In insulin resistant tissues, a threshold concentration of insulin is reached causing the cells to uptake glucose and therefore decreases blood glucose levels. Studies have shown that the high levels of insulin resulting from insulin resistance might enhance insulin resistance.<ref name=name/>\n\nStudies on mice with genetically reduced circulating insulin suggest that hyperinsulinemia plays a causal role in high fat diet-induced obesity. In this study, mice with reduced insulin levels expended more energy and had fat cells that were reprogrammed to burn some energy as heat.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Mehran|first=Arya E. |author2=Nicole M. Templeman |author3=G. Stefano Brigidi |author4=Gareth E. Lim |author5=Kwan-Yi Chu |author6=Xiaoke Hu |author7=Jose Diego Botezelli |author8=Ali Asadi |author9=Bradford G. Hoffman |author10=Timothy J. Kieffer |author11=Shernaz X. Bamji |author12=Susanne M. Clee |author13=James D. Johnson |title=Hyperinsulinemia Drives Diet-Induced Obesity Independently of Brain Insulin Production|journal=Cell Metabolism|date=6 Dec 2012|volume=16|issue=5|pages=723\u201337|doi=10.1016/j.cmet.2012.10.019 |pmid=23217255}}</ref>\n\nHyperinsulinemia in neonates can be the result of a variety of environmental and genetic factors. If the mother of the infant is a diabetic, and does not properly control her blood glucose levels, the hyperglycemic maternal blood can create a hyperglycemic environment in the fetus. To compensate for the increased blood glucose levels, fetal pancreatic beta cells can undergo [[hyperplasia]]. The rapid division of beta cells results in increased levels of insulin being secreted to compensate for the high blood glucose levels. Following birth, the hyperglycemic maternal blood is no longer accessible to the neonate resulting in a rapid drop in the newborn\u2019s blood glucose levels. As insulin levels are still elevated this may result in hypoglycemia.  To treat the condition, high concentration doses of glucose are given to the neonate as required maintaining normal blood glucose levels. The hyperinsulinemia condition subsides after one to two days.<ref>Ferry, R.J. (2010). [http://emedicine.medscape.com/article/921258-clinical#a0218 Hyperinsulinism] \"Medscape\".</ref>\n\n==Symptoms==\nThere are often no visible symptoms of hyperinsulinemia unless [[hypoglycaemia]] ([[low blood sugar]]) is present.{{Citation needed|date=October 2016}}\n\nSome patients may experience a variety of symptoms when [[hypoglycaemia]] is present, including:<ref>[http://www.diabetes.co.uk/hyperinsulinemia.html Hyperinsulinemia]</ref>\n* Temporary muscle weakness\n* Brain fog\n* [[Fatigue (medical)|Fatigue]]\n* Temporary thought disorder, or inability to concentrate\n* Visual problems such as [[blurred vision]] or [[double vision]]\n* Headaches\n* Shaking/Trembling\n* Thirst\n\nIf a person experiences any of these [[symptoms]], a visit to a qualified [[medical practitioner]] is advised, and diagnostic blood testing may be required.\n\n==Causes==\nPossible causes include:{{citation needed|date=November 2016}}\n* [[Neoplasm]]\n* [[Pancreatic cancer]]\n* [[Polycystic ovary syndrome]] (PCOS)\n* [[Trans fat]]s{{hsp}}<ref>\n {{\n  cite journal|\n  title=mice fed a diet enriched in t10,c12-CLA (0.4% w/w) for 4 weeks developed lipoatrophy, hyperinsulinemia, and fatty liver, whereas diets enriched in c9,t11-CLA and LA had no significant effect ; from google (hyperinsulinemia trans fat) result 2| pmid=12235171 | volume=43 | issue=9 |vauthors=Cl\u00e9ment L, Poirier H, Niot I, Bocher V, Guerre-Millo M, Krief S, Staels B, Besnard P| journal=J Lipid Res| pages=1400\u201309| year=2002 | doi=10.1194/jlr.M20008-JLR200 }}\n  </ref>\n\n===Link to obesity===\nSince hyperinsulinemia and [[obesity]] are so closely linked it is hard to determine whether hyperinsulinemia causes obesity or obesity causes hyperinsulinemia, or both.\n\nObesity is characterized by an excess of [[adipose tissue]] \u2013 insulin increases the synthesis of fatty acids from glucose, facilitates the entry of glucose into adipocytes and inhibits breakdown of fat in adipocytes.<ref>[http://arbl.cvmbs.colostate.edu/hbooks/pathphys/endocrine/pancreas/insulin_phys.html Physiologic Effects of Insulin]</ref>\n\nOn the other hand, adipose tissue is known to secrete various [[metabolites]], [[hormones]] and [[cytokines]] that may play a role in causing hyperinsulinemia.<ref name=\"pmid10842660\">{{cite journal|last=Matsuzawa|first=Y|author2=Fanahashi T |author3=Nakamura T |title=Moleculare mechanism of metabolic syndrome X: contribution of adiposcyte-derived bioactive substances|journal=Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences|year=1999|volume=892|issue=1|pages=146\u201354|doi=10.1111/j.1749-6632.1999.tb07793.x|pmid=10842660|bibcode=1999NYASA.892..146M}}</ref> Specifically cytokines secreted by adipose tissue directly affect the insulin signalling cascade, and thus insulin secretion.<ref name=\"pmid11344187\">{{cite journal|last=Weyer|first=C|author2=Funahachi T |author3=Tanaka S |author4=Hotta K |author5=Matsuzawa Y |author6=Pratley RE |author7=Tataranni PA |title=Hypoadiponectinemia in obesity and type 2 diabetes: close association with insulin resistance and hyperinsulinemia|journal=The Journal of Clinical Endocrinology & Metabolism|year=2011|volume=86|issue=5|pages=1930\u201335|pmid=11344187|doi=10.1210/jcem.86.5.7463}}</ref> [[Adiponectin]]s are cytokines that are inversely related to percent body fat; that is people with a low body fat will have higher concentrations of adiponectins where as people with high body fat will have lower concentrations of adiponectins.  Weyer \"et al,.\" (2011) reported that hyperinsulinemia is strongly associated with low adiponectin concentrations in obese people, though whether low adiponectin has a causal role in hyperinsulinemia remains to be established.<ref name=\"pmid11344187\" />\n* May lead to [[hypoglycemia]] or [[diabetes]]\n* Increased risk of [[PCOS]]\n* Increased synthesis of [[VLDL]] ([[hypertriglyceridemia]])\n* [[Hypertension]] (insulin increases [[sodium]] retention by the [[renal tubules]])\n* [[Coronary Artery Disease]] (increased insulin damages [[endothelial cells]])\n* Increased risk of [[cardiovascular disease]]\n* Weight gain and lethargy (possibly connected to an underactive [[thyroid]])\n* Obesity and hyperinsulinemia have some links with some types of cancer<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1038/cddis.2015.381|pmid = 26720346| pmc=4720912| title=Obesity and cancer, a case for insulin signaling| journal=Cell Death and Disease| volume=6| issue=12| pages=e2037| year=2015| last1=Poloz| first1=Y.| last2=Stambolic| first2=V.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |pmid = 27368923|year = 2016|last1 = Vigneri|first1 = R.|title = Insulin, insulin receptors, and cancer|journal = Journal of Endocrinological Investigation|volume = 39|issue = 12|pages = 1365\u20131376|last2 = Goldfine|first2 = I. D.|last3 = Frittitta|first3 = L.|doi = 10.1007/s40618-016-0508-7}}</ref>\n\n==Diagnosis==\n\nDiagnosis can be made by checking fasting and post prandial insulin levels either with normal meal or with 100g of oral glucose.{{Citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\n==Treatment==\nTreatment is typically achieved via diet and [[exercise]], although [[metformin]] may be used to reduce [[insulin]] levels in some patients (typically where obesity is present).  A referral to a [[dietician]] is beneficial. Another method used to lower excessively high insulin levels is [[cinnamon]] as was demonstrated when supplemented in clinical human trials.<ref name=\"pmid17924872\">{{cite journal|last=Solomon|first=TP|author2=Blannin, AK|title=Effects of short-term cinnamon ingestion on in vivo glucose tolerance.|journal=Diabetes, Obesity & Metabolism|date=November 2007|volume=9|issue=6|pages=895\u2013901|doi=10.1111/j.1463-1326.2006.00694.x|pmid=17924872}}</ref>\n\nA healthy diet that is low in simple [[sugars]] and processed [[carbohydrates]], and high in [[fiber]], and vegetable [[protein]] is often recommended.  This includes replacing white bread with whole-grain bread, reducing intake of foods composed primarily of starch such as potatoes, and increasing intake of [[legumes]] and green vegetables, particularly [[soy]].<ref name=\"pmid18175751\">{{cite journal|last=Villegas|first=R|author2=Gao, YT |author3=Yang, G |author4=Li, HL |author5=Elasy, TA |author6=Zheng, W |author7= Shu, XO |title=Legume and soy food intake and the incidence of type 2 diabetes in the Shanghai Women's Health Study|journal=The American Journal of Clinical Nutrition|date=January 2008|volume=87|issue=1|pages=162\u20137|pmid=18175751|pmc=2361384|url=http://ajcn.nutrition.org/content/87/1/162|doi=10.1093/ajcn/87.1.162}}</ref>\n\nRegular monitoring of weight, [[blood sugar]], and [[insulin]] are advised, as hyperinsulinemia may develop into [[diabetes mellitus type 2]].{{Citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\nIt has been shown in many studies that [[physical exercise]] improves insulin sensitivity.<ref name=\"pmid19793849\">{{cite journal|last=Solomon|first=Thomas P|author2=Haus JM |author3=Kelly KR |author4=Cook MD |author5=Riccardi M |author6=Rocco M |author7=Kashyap SR |author8=Barkowkis H |author9=Kirwan JP  |title=Randomized trial on the effects of a 7-d low-glycemic diet and exercise intervention on insulin resistance in older obese humans|journal=Am J Clin Nutr|year=2009|volume=90|issue=5|pages=1222\u201329|doi=10.3945/ajcn.2009.28293|pmid=19793849|pmc=2762157}}</ref> The mechanism of exercise on improving insulin sensitivity is not well understood however it is thought that exercise causes the glucose receptor [[GLUT4]] to translocate to the membrane.<ref name=\"pmid7597034\">{{cite journal|last=Lund|first=S|author2=Holman GD |author3=Schmitz O |author4=Pedersen O |title=Contraction stimulates translocation of glucose transporter GLUT4 in skeletal muscle through a mechanism distinct from that of insulin|journal=Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A.|year=1995|volume=92|issue=13|pages=5817\u20135821|doi=10.1073/pnas.92.13.5817|pmid=7597034|pmc=41592|bibcode=1995PNAS...92.5817L}}</ref> As more GLUT4 receptors are present on the membrane more glucose is taken up into cells decreasing blood glucose levels which then causes decreased insulin secretion and some alleviation of hyperinsulinemia.<ref name=\"pmid19793849\" /> Another proposed mechanism of improved insulin sensitivity by exercise is through [[AMPK]] activity.<ref name=\"pmid19793849\" /> The beneficial effect of exercise on hyperinsulinemia was shown in a study by Solomon et al. (2009), where they found that improving fitness through exercise significantly decreases blood insulin concentrations.<ref name=\"pmid19793849\" />\n\n==Common misconceptions==\n* Hyperinsulinemia is often mistaken for [[diabetes]] or [[hypoglycaemia]].  These are separate, albeit related, conditions.  Treatment may overlap for these conditions, but medical advice should always be sought.{{Citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Metabolic syndrome]] (Syndrome X)\n* [[Acanthosis nigricans]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n| ICD9            = {{ICD9|251.6}}\n| SNOMED CT       = 83469008\n}}\n\n* {{eMedicine|ped|1075}}\n\n[[Category:Disorders of endocrine pancreas]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Abnormal increase in insulin in the bloodstream relative to glucose}}\n{{Infobox medical condition (new) \n| name            =  \n| image           = InsulinMonomer.jpg \n| caption         = Insulin binding to its receptor \n| pronounce       =  \n| field           =  \n| synonyms        = '''Hyperinsulinaemia'''\n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n'''Hyperinsulinemia''',  is a condition in which there are excess levels of [[insulin]] circulating in the blood relative to the level of glucose. While it is often mistaken for [[diabetes]] or [[hyperglycaemia]], hyperinsulinemia can result from a variety of metabolic diseases and conditions. While hyperinsulinemia is often seen in people with early stage type 2 diabetes mellitus, it is not the cause of the condition and is only one symptom of the disease. Type 1 diabetes only occurs when pancreatic beta-cell function is impaired. Hyperinsulinemia can be seen in a variety of conditions including [[diabetes mellitus type 2]], in neonates and in drug induced hyperinsulinemia. It can also occur in congenital hyperinsulism, including [[nesidioblastosis]].\n\nHyperinsulinemia is associated with [[hypertension]], [[obesity]], [[dyslipidemia]], and [[glucose intolerance]].<ref name=\"pmid3884667\">{{cite journal|last=Modan|first=Michaela|author2=Halkin H |author3=Almog S |author4=Lusky A |author5=Eshkol A |author6=Shefi M |author7=Shitrit A |author8=Fuchs Z. |title=Hyperinsulinemia: A link between hypertension obesity and glucose intolerance|journal=J. Clin. Invest.|date=March 1985|volume=75|issue=3|pages=809\u201317|doi=10.1172/JCI111776|pmid=3884667|pmc=423608}}</ref> These conditions are collectively known as [[Metabolic syndrome]].<ref name=\"pmid19435961\">{{cite journal|last=Danker|first=Rache|author2=Chetrit A |author3=Shanik MH |author4=Raz I |author5=Roth J |title=Basal-stat hyperinsulinemia in healthy normoglycemic adults is predictive of type 2 diabetes over a 24-year follow-up|journal=Diabetes Care|date=August 2009|volume=32|issue=8|pages=1464\u201366|doi=10.2337/dc09-0153|pmid=19435961|pmc=2713622}}</ref> This close association between hyperinsulinemia and conditions of metabolic syndrome suggest related or common mechanisms of pathogenicity.<ref name=\"pmid3884667\" /> Hyperinsulinemia has been shown to \"play a role in obese [[hypertension]] by increasing renal sodium retention\".<ref name=\"pmid3884667\" />\n\nIn type 2 diabetes, the cells of the body become resistant to the effects of insulin as the receptors which bind to the hormone become less sensitive to insulin concentrations resulting in hyperinsulinemia and disturbances in insulin release.<ref name=\"name\">{{cite journal | last1 = Shanik | first1 = M.H. | last2 = Yuping | first2 = X. | last3 = Skrha | first3 = J. | last4 = Danker | first4 = R. | last5 = Zick | first5 = Y. | last6 = Roth | first6 = J. | year = 2008 | title = Insulin Resistance and Hyperinsulinemia | url = http://care.diabetesjournals.org/content/31/Supplement_2/S262.full | journal = Diabetes Care | volume = 31 | issue = 2| pages = S262\u201368 | doi =  10.2337/dc08-s264| pmid = 18227495 }}</ref> With a reduced response to insulin, the [[beta cells]] of the pancreas secrete increasing amounts of insulin in response to the continued high blood glucose levels resulting in hyperinsulinemia. In insulin resistant tissues, a threshold concentration of insulin is reached causing the cells to uptake glucose and therefore decreases blood glucose levels. Studies have shown that the high levels of insulin resulting from insulin resistance might enhance insulin resistance.<ref name=name/>\n\nStudies on mice with genetically reduced circulating insulin suggest that hyperinsulinemia plays a causal role in high fat diet-induced obesity. In this study, mice with reduced insulin levels expended more energy and had fat cells that were reprogrammed to burn some energy as heat.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Mehran|first=Arya E. |author2=Nicole M. Templeman |author3=G. Stefano Brigidi |author4=Gareth E. Lim |author5=Kwan-Yi Chu |author6=Xiaoke Hu |author7=Jose Diego Botezelli |author8=Ali Asadi |author9=Bradford G. Hoffman |author10=Timothy J. Kieffer |author11=Shernaz X. Bamji |author12=Susanne M. Clee |author13=James D. Johnson |title=Hyperinsulinemia Drives Diet-Induced Obesity Independently of Brain Insulin Production|journal=Cell Metabolism|date=6 Dec 2012|volume=16|issue=5|pages=723\u201337|doi=10.1016/j.cmet.2012.10.019 |pmid=23217255}}</ref>\n\nHyperinsulinemia in neonates can be the result of a variety of environmental and genetic factors. If the mother of the infant is a diabetic, and does not properly control her blood glucose levels, the hyperglycemic maternal blood can create a hyperglycemic environment in the fetus. To compensate for the increased blood glucose levels, fetal pancreatic beta cells can undergo [[hyperplasia]]. The rapid division of beta cells results in increased levels of insulin being secreted to compensate for the high blood glucose levels. Following birth, the hyperglycemic maternal blood is no longer accessible to the neonate resulting in a rapid drop in the newborn\u2019s blood glucose levels. As insulin levels are still elevated this may result in hypoglycemia.  To treat the condition, high concentration doses of glucose are given to the neonate as required maintaining normal blood glucose levels. The hyperinsulinemia condition subsides after one to two days.<ref>Ferry, R.J. (2010). [http://emedicine.medscape.com/article/921258-clinical#a0218 Hyperinsulinism] \"Medscape\".</ref>\n\n==Symptoms==\nThere are often no visible symptoms of hyperinsulinemia unless [[hypoglycaemia]] ([[low blood sugar]]) is present.{{Citation needed|date=October 2016}}\n\nSome patients may experience a variety of symptoms when [[hypoglycaemia]] is present, including:<ref>[http://www.diabetes.co.uk/hyperinsulinemia.html Hyperinsulinemia]</ref>\n* Temporary muscle weakness\n* Brain fog\n* [[Fatigue (medical)|Fatigue]]\n* Temporary thought disorder, or inability to concentrate\n* Visual problems such as [[blurred vision]] or [[double vision]]\n* Headaches\n* Shaking/Trembling\n* Thirst\n\nIf a person experiences any of these [[symptoms]], a visit to a qualified [[medical practitioner]] is advised, and diagnostic blood testing may be required.\n\n==Causes==\nPossible causes include:{{citation needed|date=November 2016}}\n* [[Neoplasm]]\n* [[Pancreatic cancer]]\n* [[Polycystic ovary syndrome]] (PCOS)\n* [[Trans fat]]s{{hsp}}<ref>\n {{\n  cite journal|\n  title=mice fed a diet enriched in t10,c12-CLA (0.4% w/w) for 4 weeks developed lipoatrophy, hyperinsulinemia, and fatty liver, whereas diets enriched in c9,t11-CLA and LA had no significant effect ; from google (hyperinsulinemia trans fat) result 2| pmid=12235171 | volume=43 | issue=9 |vauthors=Cl\u00e9ment L, Poirier H, Niot I, Bocher V, Guerre-Millo M, Krief S, Staels B, Besnard P| journal=J Lipid Res| pages=1400\u201309| year=2002 | doi=10.1194/jlr.M20008-JLR200 }}\n  </ref>\n\n===Link to obesity===\nSince hyperinsulinemia and [[obesity]] are so closely linked it is hard to determine whether hyperinsulinemia causes obesity or obesity causes hyperinsulinemia, or both.\n\nObesity is characterized by an excess of [[adipose tissue]] \u2013 insulin increases the synthesis of fatty acids from glucose, facilitates the entry of glucose into adipocytes and inhibits breakdown of fat in adipocytes.<ref>[http://arbl.cvmbs.colostate.edu/hbooks/pathphys/endocrine/pancreas/insulin_phys.html Physiologic Effects of Insulin]</ref>\n\nOn the other hand, adipose tissue is known to secrete various [[metabolites]], [[hormones]] and [[cytokines]] that may play a role in causing hyperinsulinemia.<ref name=\"pmid10842660\">{{cite journal|last=Matsuzawa|first=Y|author2=Fanahashi T |author3=Nakamura T |title=Moleculare mechanism of metabolic syndrome X: contribution of adiposcyte-derived bioactive substances|journal=Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences|year=1999|volume=892|issue=1|pages=146\u201354|doi=10.1111/j.1749-6632.1999.tb07793.x|pmid=10842660|bibcode=1999NYASA.892..146M}}</ref> Specifically cytokines secreted by adipose tissue directly affect the insulin signalling cascade, and thus insulin secretion.<ref name=\"pmid11344187\">{{cite journal|last=Weyer|first=C|author2=Funahachi T |author3=Tanaka S |author4=Hotta K |author5=Matsuzawa Y |author6=Pratley RE |author7=Tataranni PA |title=Hypoadiponectinemia in obesity and type 2 diabetes: close association with insulin resistance and hyperinsulinemia|journal=The Journal of Clinical Endocrinology & Metabolism|year=2011|volume=86|issue=5|pages=1930\u201335|pmid=11344187|doi=10.1210/jcem.86.5.7463}}</ref> [[Adiponectin]]s are cytokines that are inversely related to percent body fat; that is people with a low body fat will have higher concentrations of adiponectins where as people with high body fat will have lower concentrations of adiponectins.  Weyer \"et al,.\" (2011) reported that hyperinsulinemia is strongly associated with low adiponectin concentrations in obese people, though whether low adiponectin has a causal role in hyperinsulinemia remains to be established.<ref name=\"pmid11344187\" />\n* May lead to [[hypoglycemia]] or [[diabetes]]\n* Increased risk of [[PCOS]]\n* Increased synthesis of [[VLDL]] ([[hypertriglyceridemia]])\n* [[Hypertension]] (insulin increases [[sodium]] retention by the [[renal tubules]])\n* [[Coronary Artery Disease]] (increased insulin damages [[endothelial cells]])\n* Increased risk of [[cardiovascular disease]]\n* Weight gain and lethargy (possibly connected to an underactive [[thyroid]])\n* Obesity and hyperinsulinemia have some links with some types of cancer<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1038/cddis.2015.381|pmid = 26720346| pmc=4720912| title=Obesity and cancer, a case for insulin signaling| journal=Cell Death and Disease| volume=6| issue=12| pages=e2037| year=2015| last1=Poloz| first1=Y.| last2=Stambolic| first2=V.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |pmid = 27368923|year = 2016|last1 = Vigneri|first1 = R.|title = Insulin, insulin receptors, and cancer|journal = Journal of Endocrinological Investigation|volume = 39|issue = 12|pages = 1365\u20131376|last2 = Goldfine|first2 = I. D.|last3 = Frittitta|first3 = L.|doi = 10.1007/s40618-016-0508-7}}</ref>\n\n==Diagnosis==\n\nDiagnosis can be made by checking fasting and post prandial insulin levels either with normal meal or with 100g of oral glucose.{{Citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\n==Treatment==\nTreatment is typically achieved via diet and [[exercise]], although [[metformin]] may be used to reduce [[insulin]] levels in some patients (typically where obesity is present).  A referral to a [[dietician]] is beneficial. Another method used to lower excessively high insulin levels is [[cinnamon]] as was demonstrated when supplemented in clinical human trials.<ref name=\"pmid17924872\">{{cite journal|last=Solomon|first=TP|author2=Blannin, AK|title=Effects of short-term cinnamon ingestion on in vivo glucose tolerance.|journal=Diabetes, Obesity & Metabolism|date=November 2007|volume=9|issue=6|pages=895\u2013901|doi=10.1111/j.1463-1326.2006.00694.x|pmid=17924872}}</ref>\n\nA healthy diet that is low in simple [[sugars]] and processed [[carbohydrates]], and high in [[fiber]], and vegetable [[protein]] is often recommended.  This includes replacing white bread with whole-grain bread, reducing intake of foods composed primarily of starch such as potatoes, and increasing intake of [[legumes]] and green vegetables, particularly [[soy]].<ref name=\"pmid18175751\">{{cite journal|last=Villegas|first=R|author2=Gao, YT |author3=Yang, G |author4=Li, HL |author5=Elasy, TA |author6=Zheng, W |author7= Shu, XO |title=Legume and soy food intake and the incidence of type 2 diabetes in the Shanghai Women's Health Study|journal=The American Journal of Clinical Nutrition|date=January 2008|volume=87|issue=1|pages=162\u20137|pmid=18175751|pmc=2361384|url=http://ajcn.nutrition.org/content/87/1/162|doi=10.1093/ajcn/87.1.162}}</ref>\n\nRegular monitoring of weight, [[blood sugar]], and [[insulin]] are advised, as hyperinsulinemia may develop into [[diabetes mellitus type 2]].{{Citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\nIt has been shown in many studies that [[physical exercise]] improves insulin sensitivity.<ref name=\"pmid19793849\">{{cite journal|last=Solomon|first=Thomas P|author2=Haus JM |author3=Kelly KR |author4=Cook MD |author5=Riccardi M |author6=Rocco M |author7=Kashyap SR |author8=Barkowkis H |author9=Kirwan JP  |title=Randomized trial on the effects of a 7-d low-glycemic diet and exercise intervention on insulin resistance in older obese humans|journal=Am J Clin Nutr|year=2009|volume=90|issue=5|pages=1222\u201329|doi=10.3945/ajcn.2009.28293|pmid=19793849|pmc=2762157}}</ref> The mechanism of exercise on improving insulin sensitivity is not well understood however it is thought that exercise causes the glucose receptor [[GLUT4]] to translocate to the membrane.<ref name=\"pmid7597034\">{{cite journal|last=Lund|first=S|author2=Holman GD |author3=Schmitz O |author4=Pedersen O |title=Contraction stimulates translocation of glucose transporter GLUT4 in skeletal muscle through a mechanism distinct from that of insulin|journal=Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A.|year=1995|volume=92|issue=13|pages=5817\u20135821|doi=10.1073/pnas.92.13.5817|pmid=7597034|pmc=41592|bibcode=1995PNAS...92.5817L}}</ref> As more GLUT4 receptors are present on the membrane more glucose is taken up into cells decreasing blood glucose levels which then causes decreased insulin secretion and some alleviation of hyperinsulinemia.<ref name=\"pmid19793849\" /> Another proposed mechanism of improved insulin sensitivity by exercise is through [[AMPK]] activity.<ref name=\"pmid19793849\" /> The beneficial effect of exercise on hyperinsulinemia was shown in a study by Solomon et al. (2009), where they found that improving fitness through exercise significantly decreases blood insulin concentrations.<ref name=\"pmid19793849\" />\n\n==Common misconceptions==\n* Hyperinsulinemia is often mistaken for [[diabetes]] or [[hypoglycaemia]].  These are separate, albeit related, conditions.  Treatment may overlap for these conditions, but medical advice should always be sought.{{Citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Metabolic syndrome]] (Syndrome X)\n* [[Acanthosis nigricans]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n|   ICD9        = {{ICD9|251.6}} \n}}\n\n* {{eMedicine|ped|1075}}\n\n[[Category:Disorders of endocrine pancreas]]\n", "name_user": "Dismanet", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding new medical resources.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperinsulinemia"}
